281
00:18:13,157 --> 00:18:16,009
We have 6 homicides
in a 7-mile radius in east Cleveland.

282
00:18:16,340 --> 00:18:19,544
This small zone indicates that's he's
a geographically stable offender.

283
00:18:19,884 --> 00:18:22,430
This type of offender is
characterized as young,

284
00:18:22,643 --> 00:18:24,766
socially immature, of
average intelligence,

285
00:18:24,891 --> 00:18:27,080
with psychopathic personality traits.

286
00:18:27,205 --> 00:18:30,001
They also usually live alone
and have an antisocial nature.

287
00:18:30,126 --> 00:18:32,693
A serial killer's first
murder is very telling.

288
00:18:32,904 --> 00:18:34,769
This unsub's first murder,
he chose the m. o.

289
00:18:34,894 --> 00:18:37,473
of Cleveland's own
butcher of Kingsbury run.

290
00:18:37,598 --> 00:18:40,065
The butcher isn't as well known
as other famous serial killers,

291
00:18:40,190 --> 00:18:41,943
but he is a local legend.

292
00:18:42,194 --> 00:18:45,164
And because he picked the butcher,
we believe he's a native of Cleveland

293
00:18:45,428 --> 00:18:47,541
and probably grew up hearing
stories of the butcher.

294
00:18:47,666 --> 00:18:50,169
This is someone who is obsessed
with serial killers.

295
00:18:50,338 --> 00:18:52,043
His PC will be filled with research.

296
00:18:52,168 --> 00:18:54,387
He'll have abundant images
of murderers on his computer

297
00:18:54,512 --> 00:18:56,091
and possibly even snuff films.

298
00:18:56,216 --> 00:18:58,212
He uses these like pornography.

299
00:18:58,337 --> 00:19:01,639
They provide some sort
of sexual release.

300
00:19:17,585 --> 00:19:20,032
I think he went back
to relive his crime.

301
00:19:20,464 --> 00:19:23,440
When Zoe showed up,
she became a victim of opportunity.

302
00:19:23,565 --> 00:19:25,777
It's the same theory
we arrived at on the plane.

303
00:19:25,902 --> 00:19:27,679
He strangled her with her own scarf.

304
00:19:27,804 --> 00:19:30,008
He didn't plan it.
I think she surprised him.

305
00:19:31,527 --> 00:19:32,527
I told her

306
00:19:32,993 --> 00:19:36,265
not to stop until she found the answers
she was looking for.

307
00:19:37,417 --> 00:19:39,468
I didn't think she would
go to a crime scene.

308
00:19:39,742 --> 00:19:41,593
Her mom said 
that she that does all the time.

309
00:19:41,718 --> 00:19:43,524
She probably would have gone anyway.

310
00:19:43,649 --> 00:19:45,042
But it's because of what I said

311
00:19:45,167 --> 00:19:47,309
that she was encouraged
to go there last night.

312
00:19:47,686 --> 00:19:49,281
What are you doing?

313
00:19:49,406 --> 00:19:51,302
She came to me and I dismissed her.

314
00:19:52,303 --> 00:19:53,774
Try not to personalize it.

315
00:19:55,367 --> 00:19:58,610
I was the last one she talked to
before she was murdered.

316
00:19:59,152 --> 00:20:01,150
How is this not personal, Aaron?

317
00:20:04,751 --> 00:20:05,951
It's personal.

318
00:20:06,418 --> 00:20:09,415
That doesn't change how we go
about finding her killer.

319
00:20:12,065 --> 00:20:15,671
We know that violent criminals develop
a signature over a series of crimes.

320
00:20:16,126 --> 00:20:18,882
If he's young, he probably hasn't
even figured out what his is yet.

321
00:20:20,805 --> 00:20:23,341
Find the signature,
we can link the crimes.

322
00:20:23,466 --> 00:20:26,598
He probably monitoring the news, seeing
if the police have connected them yet.

323
00:20:26,912 --> 00:20:29,340
We can use that.
We can utilize the media.

324
00:20:29,465 --> 00:20:31,479
And I think I know
who we can talk to.

325
